al pneumonia on August 2, 1910 at 43, the Evening Capital ran a front-page obituary: 'She was a woman of high culture and deep learning and rare intellectuality.' In 1916 the St. Anne's Society installed a carved stone sedilia set in her memory — ceremonial seats for officiating clergy, still in the chancel of St. Anne's Church, Annapolis.","number":1}],"cross_connections":[],"bio":{"display_name":"Carrie Jennings Willcox","first_name":"Carrie","last_name":"Willcox","maiden_name":"Willcox","married_names":["Willcox"]},"residence":{},"baptism":{},"research_tags":[],"research_sources":[],"documents":[],"naming_inspiration":[],"institutions":[{"institution_id":"INST114"}],"landmarks":[],"artworks":[],"quotes":[],"military_service":[],"slug":"carrie-willcox-1867"},"X02013":{"id":"X02013","is_placeholder":false,"gender":"male","has_descendants_documented":true,"classification":{"include_in_path_calculation":false,"descent_from_thomas_hooker":false,"descent_from_john_talcott":false,"is_thomas_descendant":false,"is_talcott_descendant":false,"is_easter_egg":false},"birth":{"year":1798,"month":6,"day":14},"death":{"year":1869,"month":6,"day":2},"burial":{"cemetery_id":"CEM009"},"parents":{},"marriages":[{"marriage_number":1,"spouse_id":"HD0726","children_ids":["HD2965","HD0731"]}],"number_of_marriages":1,"tags":[],"sources":[{"short":"FindAGrave"}],"notable":{"is_notable":true,"notable_category":["law","politics"],"notable_blurb":"The marshal who held the Amistad captives","primary_url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Amistad_(schooner)","primary_url_label":"Amistad case — Wikipedia"},"narrative_blocks":[{"category":"law","header":"The marshal who held the Amistad captives","body":"Appointed United States Marshal for Connecticut by Andrew Jackson in 1831, Willcox took custody of the kidnapped Africans of the schooner Amistad when they were brought to New Haven in 1839. He held them through the long case that climbed to the Supreme Court.","number":1},{"category":"law","header":"He later carried out the captives' release","body":"When the courts ruled for the Africans, it fell to Willcox to free them from federal custody. President Polk afterward named him collector of customs for the port of New Haven.","number":2}],"cross_connections":[{"type":"legal_adversary_ally","related_id":"HD0867","display_label":"Both central figures in the Amistad case — Willcox as federal marshal holding the captives, Leavitt as the abolitionist organizing their legal defense.","link_text":"Rev. Joshua Leavitt"},{"type":"amistad_connection","related_id":"H00697","display_label":"Cowles housed a Mende girl in his Farmington home after the Supreme Court freed the captives; Willcox had administered their federal custody throughout the trial.","link_text":"Horace Cowles"},{"type":"amistad_connection","related_id":"H00698","display_label":"Held the Mende during trial — Cowles housed one after release","link_text":"Major Timothy Cowles","description":"Norris Willcox held the Mende captives in federal custody during their trial. After the Supreme Court freed them in March 1841, the Mende were brought to Farmington, where Major Timothy Cowles was among the families who sheltered one of the freed Mende girls."}],"bio":{"display_name":"Norris Willcox","first_name":"Norris","last_name":"Willcox","married_names":[]},"residence":{},"baptism":{},"research_tags":[],"research_sources":[],"documents":[],"naming_inspiration":[],"institutions":[],"landmarks":[],"artworks":[],"quotes":[],"military_service":[],"slug":"norris-willcox-1798"},"HD0726":{"id":"HD0726","has_descendants_documented":true,"classification":{"include_in_path_calculation":true,"generation_from_thomas":7,"descent_from_thomas_hooker":true,"descent_from_john_talcott":false,"is_thomas_descendant":true,"is_talcott_descendant":false,"is_easter_egg":false},"birth":{"year":1798,"month":9,"day":22,"city":"Berlin","state":"Connecticut"},"parents":{"father_id":"H00587","mother_research_notes":"Lucy Beckley Hart","mothe